E'ci</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=qaedainmagikot@themagicianstower>Qaedain Magikot</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 903<br> <font color=#333333>(2/20/03 12:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8834.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: I would go for the crowbar option</span><hr size=1> Windows 2000 has a faster 3d subsystem than Windows XP.<br>
<br>
In the range of 15 FPS or 1100 3dmarks.<br>
<br>
I ran an average series of tests on my one PC. Fresh install of windows XP, 10 3dmark 2001 runs. Average score was 9100.<br>
<br>
I reformatted the computer and installed Windows 2000, same drivers, same driver order. Out of 10 3dmark runs, the average score was 10200. That's a hefty jump.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, a fresh boot of Windows XP with a stripped down service set, and no Luna uses a whopping 130mb. Windows 2000 Pro with the same stripped down service set, disabled POSIX, OSR2, increase addresscache size, amongst other tweaks...Namely an identical tweak set, netted 100mb of RAM use upon boot. That's with 512mb of RAM. A 30 extra MB of RAM to use is nothing to fool around with. I'll take it.<br>
<br>
All the drivers that come with XP, especially for video and sound, are extremely poor. The XP video drivers rely on software emulation of 3d to complete tasks. The performance is appalling.<br>
<br>
Activation (Without DEVILS0WN) is also a pain in the arse. Not in the sense of doing it, but simply because I don't believe I should be limited to a certain amount of hardware changes every period of days.<br>
<br>
Also, NTFS version 3.0, present in Windows 2000 is significantly more stable than NTFS v3.1 in XP. Ever blew a fuse in your house and have the computer cut out, only to find that XP can't find the NTLDR (NT loader) any more?<br>
<br>
Ever had to hard-reset your PC, and find the same thing? I have, several times. I used XP for a year, and I'm going on 8 months with Windows 2000. I had the problem every 1 or 2 months with NTFS v3.1, and I've never had it with v3.0.<br>
<br>
It seems to me that v3.1 is highly volatile.<br>
<br>
Moreover, Windows XP has EXTREMELY poor SCSI/IDE RAID performance. Within the operating system itself, all programmers were told to disable ExecutiveWriteCaching.<br>
<br>
That's wonderful, but EWC allows harddrives to store data to its buffers. This store and forward method increases the throughput of the drive by up to 30 mb/s in RAID/SCSI environments....It's disabled on XP. RAID/SCSI performance is absolutely abysmal.<br>
<br>
And even when I used XP, I turned luna off, services off, uninstalled a bunch of native applications. What did I have? A slightly faster booting Windows 2000 with a slicker login UI.<br>
<br>
I'll take 2000. <p>-Qaedain Magi'kot, The Guildless One, 58 magician, Bertoxxulous<br>
