<br>
Turn off the eye candy, make sure that NTFS is installed on ALL drives (unless you are dual booting) and make sure that your device drivers are updated and XP will run just as well as 2000.<br>
<br>
As far as registration, in the 1.5 years that I have been supporting XP, the only times that i see XP wanting to re-activate are:<br>
Installing to a new hard drive<br>
Installing a burned version onto a second computer<br>
After replacing the motherboard with one of a different type<br>
<br>
<br>
It's possible (we've done it) to replace every component of the computer (except MB) without triggering the activation.  It's designed for some leeway.<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.cox.net/miiphon/eq/sig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sadeadughettafabulous>Sadeadu Ghettafabulous</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#333333>(2/21/03 5:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8834.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_cry.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: 2000 vs XP food for thought</span><hr size=1> To answer your question first ... Screensaver password would be your easiest bet, that is IF you have the ability to password protect your screensaver but this still leaves you open to your roomates simply rebooting your pc while it's running, thus risking file corruption and fragmentation. The previous instructions on setting up your pc to allow for multiple user logons and request a password are dead on but if you really want resonable security (short of someone using lophat or NTFS read utilities to hack and retrive your password) then I'd say upgrade the OS if your hardware will support it. <br>
<br>
You have the benefit of a large collection of eggheads here that would be glad to help or advise as we can (no offense meant fellow eggheads) <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Based on what info you gave us I'd say the best logical choice if your BIOS allows it is in fact the supervisor password. Short of removing your cmos battery or system jumper on the motherboard itself to reset factory defaults they will have no way to bypass it.<br>
<br>
Also - <br>
<br>
I agree on the XP Pro/Home minus bloated bells and whistles = Win2k Professional. My experience has been that the setup routine out of the box is faster and easier on XP than win2k and the backward compatibility features in XP are nice. However, knowing what to turn off can be a smidge intimidating for the &quot;average&quot; end-user. You'll be ok with either one if you do decide to upgrade and most, keyword, most, newer programs will run off the shelf on either flavor of windows.<br>
<br>
I've been doing OS (desktop) support for over a half a decade now and have to say that imho XP is friendlier to the end user than any predecessor. My biggest gripe with win2k forward was the removal of the ability to re-arrange resource allocation (IRQ and DMA settings) this can be done under win2k but it's a pain it the arse other than managing resources via bios, curiously it is still recommended as a possible solution on SOE's tech support forum for AMD/Asus folks dropping to desktop when they zone) ... but I digress further ...<br>
<br>
Lastly - Windows ME = Satan's child, Windows 2000 and XP = &quot;bleh, ok if I have to&quot; ...  Mac = way to make something intuitive and stable for &quot;joe end-user&quot; ... and Linux &gt; ALL ... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <p>Bertoxxulous
