<br>
That's a great idea.  Takes me back to the days of removable stereos in cars before the detatchable faceplate became standard.<br>
<br>
With one bay and two trays and drives you could simply swap out drives when you are gone.  If they mess up their drive reformatting and reinstalling is no big deal-just make sure it has decent antivirus that will stop any virus that can potentially alter the BIOS.  When you come home you pop your drive in and boot up with the knowledge that your system is the way you want it.<br>
I would also recommend getting trays that have locks, that way if you accidentally leave yours out and laying around they can't put it in; and they won't try to pull the drive out while the computer is running.<br>
All in all, with a bay and two drive trays, you are looking at:<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.tigerdirect.com/applications/SearchTools/item-details.asp?sku=K450-8000" target="top">Tiger Direct Drive bay plus insert---12 bucks</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.tigerdirect.com/applications/SearchTools/item-details.asp?sku=K450-8000" target="top">Extra insert---9 bucks</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
plus a second hard drive, if you don't have one already....can go 30-200 dollars depending on what you want to give them storage space wise.<br>
